## CS50P — Exceptions

Watched the CS50P lecture on exceptions — how Python deals with errors at runtime instead of crashing.

- **try/except** — run risky code inside `try`, and if it fails, `except` catches the error instead of the whole program dying
- **ValueError, NameError** — different error types signal different problems; you can catch them specifically
- **else and finally** — `else` runs only if no exception happened; `finally` runs no matter what (success or failure)
- **raise** — deliberately throw an exception yourself when something invalid happens

**Mental model:** exceptions are guardrails. Instead of the program flying off the road when it hits bad input, `try/except` catches it and lets you decide what to do next.

